- author: dlmetcalf
  body: |-
    Ah, yes.  I was referring to @Matthew.  :)   Thanks Richard.  

    Regarding Olm, you are correct, in most (but not all) jurisdictions the dedication "The Olm specification (this document) is hereby placed in the public domain." is already valid and effective without license.  In some places that doesn't work though (e.g. due to irrevocable rights protected in legislation), so it should probably be made "CC0" - which effectively means it'll be public domain where possible, or under the most open license possible where not.
  created: 2016-06-16 11:33:10.0
  id: '13006'
  issue: '12710'
  type: comment
  updateauthor: dlmetcalf
  updated: 2016-06-16 11:33:10.0
- author: richvdh
  body: |-
    It is notable that the standard CC-BY licenses explicitly do not make any statements about transfer of patents. We are keen to make it clear that we (and, importantly, any other contributors to the spec) are not claiming any patents over the documented APIs (to avoid any concerns over a future Oracle vs Google).  CC licenses are aimed at scientific and educational documents, where it is more appropriate to separate the patent from the copyright.

    I think ASLv2 is appropriate for us; the spec is versioned and built in a similar way to software, and ASL is short and to the point.
